00:06:31.930 --> 00:06:35.810
So I'm interested in
trust and, of course,

00:06:35.810 --> 00:06:40.030
this is one of these master
concepts that is defined variously,

00:06:40.030 --> 00:06:42.790
and so I'm going to
give you my definition.

00:06:42.790 --> 00:06:45.410
And it is a definition
that makes trust

00:06:45.410 --> 00:06:49.490
to be a fairly particular
kind of thing.

00:06:49.490 --> 00:06:52.710
That is, I'm not interested
in trust in the sense

00:06:52.710 --> 00:06:55.270
that I trust everyone
or everyone trusts me.

00:06:55.270 --> 00:06:56.980
It's not so generic.

00:06:56.980 --> 00:06:59.090
It's not so ambient.

00:06:59.090 --> 00:07:02.290
Really I'm interested in a
definition or an understanding

00:07:02.290 --> 00:07:04.190 position:56%
of trust where it makes sense to say

00:07:04.190 --> 00:07:07.520
that person A trusts
person B to do something.

00:07:07.520 --> 00:07:11.290
To do X. That is, and
when you do trust someone,

00:07:11.290 --> 00:07:14.510
you proceed with the expectation
that that other individual is going

00:07:14.510 --> 00:07:16.740
to do whatever it is X is.

00:07:16.740 --> 00:07:20.240
And so this is an ocean of
trust that is relational.

00:07:20.240 --> 00:07:21.540
That is, it's about relations

00:07:21.540 --> 00:07:24.180
between two parties
and it's specific.

00:07:24.180 --> 00:07:26.610
It's not that I trust
so-and-so, in general.

00:07:26.610 --> 00:07:29.760
I trust them to do something
in particular, and, of course,

00:07:29.760 --> 00:07:32.490
trust is not the same
thing as trustworthiness.

00:07:32.490 --> 00:07:35.090
You could trust someone
who wasn't trustworthy,

00:07:35.090 --> 00:07:37.860
in which case you've
made a terrible mistake.

00:07:37.860 --> 00:07:41.650
So in pulling apart trust,
there's really two features

00:07:41.650 --> 00:07:43.310
that make it complicated.

00:07:43.310 --> 00:07:47.470
And I call these vulnerability
and uncertainty.

00:07:47.470 --> 00:07:51.920
And vulnerability stems from the
fact that what B does is going

00:07:51.920 --> 00:07:55.930
to have an impact on A. That is,
A cares about what B will do,

00:07:55.930 --> 00:08:01.080
and if B does something nicely or
well, then it's going to help A

00:08:01.080 --> 00:08:03.480
and if they don't,
it's going to hurt A.

00:08:03.480 --> 00:08:06.160
So B's actions have an impact on A

00:08:06.160 --> 00:08:09.320
and that's the vulnerability
feature.

00:08:09.320 --> 00:08:11.810
But it's also the case, that
because it's all forward-looking

00:08:11.810 --> 00:08:15.270
into the future, A doesn't
know what B is going to do.

00:08:15.270 --> 00:08:16.610
That is, there's uncertainty.

00:08:16.610 --> 00:08:19.070
If the world were perfectly
predictable, we wouldn't have

00:08:19.070 --> 00:08:23.310
to worry about trust because you
would know what B is going to do.

00:08:23.310 --> 00:08:24.610
You wouldn't have to trust them.

00:08:24.610 --> 00:08:27.210
And, of course, with this
kind of general definition,

00:08:27.210 --> 00:08:28.980
trust matters in politics.

00:08:28.980 --> 00:08:30.390
It matters in the economy.

00:08:30.390 --> 00:08:32.920
It matters in social
life, generally.

00:08:32.920 --> 00:08:37.100
And certainly we're in the midst
of an election, where the issue

00:08:37.100 --> 00:08:40.220
of who trusts whom is
clearly very important.

00:08:40.220 --> 00:08:43.380
But I'm going to focus
on the economy.

00:08:43.380 --> 00:08:49.610 position:56%
So my definition of trust maps very
nicely onto the situation of credit.

00:08:49.610 --> 00:08:54.030
So if we consider that this
party A is called the creditor

00:08:54.030 --> 00:08:55.930
and B is the debtor.

00:08:55.930 --> 00:08:58.710
And this activity is
called repay the money.

00:08:58.710 --> 00:09:01.270
And the definition
applies very directly

00:09:01.270 --> 00:09:04.060
and very simply to
the issue of credit.

00:09:04.060 --> 00:09:06.810
And so does uncertainty
and vulnerability.

00:09:06.810 --> 00:09:10.130
A is uncertain about whether
B will keep her promise

00:09:10.130 --> 00:09:12.190
to repay, so you don't know.

00:09:12.190 --> 00:09:14.670
You know, you lend the money
and you hope they will repay

00:09:14.670 --> 00:09:16.890
but you aren't entirely sure.

00:09:16.890 --> 00:09:20.290
And the lender is vulnerable,
depending upon the size

00:09:20.290 --> 00:09:21.590
and the maturity of the loans.

00:09:21.590 --> 00:09:23.650
So if you lend someone
a small amount,

00:09:23.650 --> 00:09:25.230
it's not a huge vulnerability.

00:09:25.230 --> 00:09:27.820
If you lend them enough to buy a
house, it's a big vulnerability.

00:09:27.820 --> 00:09:29.330
And so forth.

00:09:29.330 --> 00:09:33.370
And, in moving forward, given
this sort of problem of trust,

00:09:33.370 --> 00:09:36.460
there's kind of a simple
recipe forward

00:09:36.460 --> 00:09:39.360
and that is either
address uncertainty.

00:09:39.360 --> 00:09:41.720
That is, gather information
to figure

00:09:41.720 --> 00:09:43.850
out well what are they going to do?

00:09:43.850 --> 00:09:45.530
Or manage vulnerability.

00:09:45.530 --> 00:09:50.480
Find ways to protect yourself
from this behavior if that occurs.

00:09:50.480 --> 00:09:53.350
So very straightforward
kind of recipe

00:09:53.350 --> 00:09:56.450
for mitigating the trust problem.

00:09:56.450 --> 00:10:01.920
And the real problem is that
you can't run a modern economy

00:10:01.920 --> 00:10:03.330
without credit.

00:10:03.330 --> 00:10:06.990
That is, this is an inescapable
problem in the modern world.

00:10:06.990 --> 00:10:09.890
Modern economies are
built around promises.

00:10:09.890 --> 00:10:13.320
Lots and lots of people are making
lots and lots of promises to lots

00:10:13.320 --> 00:10:14.670
and lots of other people.

00:10:14.670 --> 00:10:17.800
And the viability of that
really fuels the economy.

00:10:17.800 --> 00:10:21.630
If no one trusted anyone
else, we'd all, you know,

00:10:21.630 --> 00:10:23.210
we wouldn't even be
drinking the water

00:10:23.210 --> 00:10:25.170
because we'd be worried
it was poisonous.

00:10:25.170 --> 00:10:28.010
And I'm going to have a bit
of the water that Dan gave me

00:10:28.010 --> 00:10:30.370
and I trust him, you know?

00:10:30.370 --> 00:10:33.640
And life would be hard
if I couldn't.

00:10:33.640 --> 00:10:36.810
So credit is pervasive and it's
a really practical problem.

00:10:36.810 --> 00:10:39.850
That is, if you're in the
business world operating

00:10:39.850 --> 00:10:43.600
without credit makes
your life very miserable,

00:10:43.600 --> 00:10:47.130 position:56%
but it's also a theoretical issue in
the sense that people have thought

00:10:47.130 --> 00:10:49.870
for a long time how do
we solve this problem?

00:10:49.870 --> 00:10:51.190
What is the nature of this problem?

00:10:51.190 --> 00:10:54.040
How can we build institutions
that will deal with it?

00:10:54.040 --> 00:10:56.570
So I've got a nice quote
here from Walter Bagehot,

00:10:56.570 --> 00:11:00.970
who was a very famous 19th
century British Central Banker.

00:11:00.970 --> 00:11:02.650
He wrote In Lombard Street.

00:11:02.650 --> 00:11:04.580
Credit is a set of promises to pay.

00:11:04.580 --> 00:11:08.210
Will those promises be kept?

00:11:08.210 --> 00:11:14.380
So, in this talk and in my
project, I'm really focused on,

00:11:14.380 --> 00:11:18.270
in the informational side,
not so much on vulnerability,

00:11:18.270 --> 00:11:21.280
which is an important component,
but that would be another talk.

00:11:21.280 --> 00:11:26.190
I'm really looking at how do people
gather information about borrowers

00:11:26.190 --> 00:11:29.560
to reduce the uncertainty about
what those folks are going to do?

00:11:29.560 --> 00:11:33.280
Will they -- how do you answer the
question will so-and-so repay the

00:11:33.280 --> 00:11:34.580
loan I'm going to make to them?

00:11:34.580 --> 00:11:37.270
And I'm going to focus
particularly on the invention

00:11:37.270 --> 00:11:39.710 position:56%
of credit ratings and credit scores.

00:11:39.710 --> 00:11:42.200
And, as you'll learn, this is
something that was really invented

00:11:42.200 --> 00:11:45.550
in the United States and now
is quite a pervasive form

00:11:45.550 --> 00:11:47.210
of information.

00:11:47.210 --> 00:11:49.160
These, over the time
period, the time period

00:11:49.160 --> 00:11:51.400
that I'm examining,
grew in importance.

00:11:51.400 --> 00:11:55.380
And they augmented and
partially displaced older forms

00:11:55.380 --> 00:11:58.890
of information, and I'll say
a little bit more about that.

00:11:58.890 --> 00:12:02.210
And, as [inaudible] said,
I'm just going to look

00:12:02.210 --> 00:12:05.860
at the informational
side of the problem.

00:12:05.860 --> 00:12:08.630
That is, the part that
deals with uncertainty.

00:12:08.630 --> 00:12:13.090
I'm going to set aside all of
the tricks that lenders have

00:12:13.090 --> 00:12:14.980
for reducing their vulnerability.

00:12:14.980 --> 00:12:16.760 position:56%
But just to give you a sense of what

00:12:16.760 --> 00:12:19.920
such a trick might look
like, think about collateral.

00:12:19.920 --> 00:12:22.190
Collateral is a way
of saying, you know,

00:12:22.190 --> 00:12:25.020
if you don't repay me,
I'll take your house.

00:12:25.020 --> 00:12:26.320
Or I'll take your car.

00:12:26.320 --> 00:12:27.760
I'll repossess your car.

00:12:27.760 --> 00:12:31.790
That's a collateralized loan and
obviously reduces the vulnerability

00:12:31.790 --> 00:12:33.490
because it reduces the losses.

00:12:33.490 --> 00:12:37.640
So one of the interesting
things about this is

00:12:37.640 --> 00:12:39.690
that there is some
measure of continuity.

00:12:39.690 --> 00:12:43.120
That is, if you think about and
look at how people have thought

00:12:43.120 --> 00:12:47.150 position:56%
about the trustworthiness of debtors
and how to manage the problem

00:12:47.150 --> 00:12:50.800
of lending to them, there
is some folk wisdom --

00:12:50.800 --> 00:12:54.340
and I call these durable
creditor heuristics --

00:12:54.340 --> 00:12:56.590
that have existed for centuries.

00:12:56.590 --> 00:13:00.260 position:56%
And on the right-hand side, we have
the title page of a nice little book

00:13:00.260 --> 00:13:02.320
that came out of the
Bank of Philadelphia

00:13:02.320 --> 00:13:04.900
that talk about the four C's.

00:13:04.900 --> 00:13:07.530
And, if you were a lender,
here's a nice handy mnemonic.

00:13:07.530 --> 00:13:09.630
If you're going to wonder
whether you should lend money

00:13:09.630 --> 00:13:12.900
to some customer, pay
attention to their character.

00:13:12.900 --> 00:13:14.200
Their capacity.

00:13:14.200 --> 00:13:15.500
Their capital.

00:13:15.500 --> 00:13:16.800
And their collateral.

00:13:16.800 --> 00:13:18.100
Nice little handy memorable phrase.

00:13:18.100 --> 00:13:22.440
Well, going back to the early 19th
century and crossing the Atlantic.

00:13:22.440 --> 00:13:26.850
In the London Tradesmen, which is
a sort of a business advice book,

00:13:26.850 --> 00:13:30.240
