00:26:25.410 --> 00:26:27.400
Then we go to 1873.

00:26:27.400 --> 00:26:29.110
They say not much means.

00:26:29.110 --> 00:26:31.840
Honest and considered good
for any bills he may contract.

00:26:31.840 --> 00:26:34.360
Is worth about $4,000.

00:26:34.360 --> 00:26:40.260
So between 1871 and 1873, it seems
that his situation has improved.

00:26:40.260 --> 00:26:45.350
And then in 1875, we go back to the
outrageous national stereotyping.

00:26:45.350 --> 00:26:47.090
He's a good careful German.

00:26:47.090 --> 00:26:51.550
Right? So this is one of the things
that you do see in the records,

00:26:51.550 --> 00:26:53.960
is this kind of national
stereotyping

00:26:53.960 --> 00:26:57.490
and it really is a shorthand way of
talking about somebody's character.

00:26:57.490 --> 00:26:58.790
Where do they come from?

00:26:58.790 --> 00:27:00.160
What kind of a person are they?

00:27:00.160 --> 00:27:01.730
And on it goes.

00:27:01.730 --> 00:27:06.790 position:56%
That is not -- I should flip back --
this is the proprietary information

00:27:06.790 --> 00:27:09.170
that they did not share
with their customers.

00:27:09.170 --> 00:27:10.490
It's what they accumulated.

00:27:10.490 --> 00:27:13.230
It was their sort of knowledge
base, but what they sold

00:27:13.230 --> 00:27:16.220
to their customers was
stuff that looked like this.

00:27:16.220 --> 00:27:17.950
A published reference book.

00:27:17.950 --> 00:27:19.770
It looks like a phone directory,

00:27:19.770 --> 00:27:21.780
even though this is
before there are phones.

00:27:21.780 --> 00:27:23.280
But to blow it up.

00:27:23.280 --> 00:27:26.990
What you have is an
alphabetical listing of firms

00:27:26.990 --> 00:27:29.680
by the name of the proprietor.

00:27:29.680 --> 00:27:33.990
So we've got James Farrell who
it turns out is an undertaker,

00:27:33.990 --> 00:27:37.480
not someone you want to meet.

00:27:37.480 --> 00:27:39.340
And then there's a score, E2.

00:27:39.340 --> 00:27:45.760
And so if you wanted to, you know,
sell coffins to James Farrell,

00:27:45.760 --> 00:27:48.530
for example, and you wanted
to know if he's going to pay.

00:27:48.530 --> 00:27:51.250
If he's good on the coffins.

00:27:51.250 --> 00:27:54.410
Then you would look him up,
you know, as a subscriber.

00:27:54.410 --> 00:27:56.950
You'd look at the entry
and you'd go E2.

00:27:56.950 --> 00:27:59.130
Oh yeah, okay, what does that mean?

00:27:59.130 --> 00:28:03.120
And there would be a key, and
that's the stuff on the right.

00:28:03.120 --> 00:28:09.500
Let me disappear off camera
[inaudible] would basically

00:28:09.500 --> 00:28:13.210
interpret for the user the
meaning of these categories.

00:28:13.210 --> 00:28:16.610
The summary ordered categories.

00:28:16.610 --> 00:28:20.910
So the rating process that was
happening inside these firms

00:28:20.910 --> 00:28:25.450
translated ledger information
into an ordinal category system,

00:28:25.450 --> 00:28:29.110
which they then made available
to their customers and sold

00:28:29.110 --> 00:28:31.580
in these giant reference books.

00:28:31.580 --> 00:28:36.670
What is interesting is that behind
that transformational process,

00:28:36.670 --> 00:28:39.230
taking this very narrational
qualitative information

00:28:39.230 --> 00:28:43.900
and turning it into a score or
a rating, there was no method,

00:28:43.900 --> 00:28:46.950
algorithm, protocol, or procedure.

00:28:46.950 --> 00:28:49.970
It was an entire opaque mystery.

00:28:49.970 --> 00:28:54.160
They sold these ratings
to their clients.

00:28:54.160 --> 00:28:57.590
And you know when somebody
subscribed to a reference book.

00:28:57.590 --> 00:29:00.740
They got these keys to kind
of tell them what that meant.

00:29:00.740 --> 00:29:04.430
And so, in the particular example
that's probably a little too fine

00:29:04.430 --> 00:29:07.060
grained for you to see,
at the top is double A.

00:29:07.060 --> 00:29:09.640
And that means the
pecuniary strength

00:29:09.640 --> 00:29:12.140
of the firm is rated
over a million dollars.

00:29:12.140 --> 00:29:13.440
That's a big firm.

00:29:13.440 --> 00:29:17.380
And so, if you looked up some firm
and it had double A attached to it,

00:29:17.380 --> 00:29:20.010
you probably would conclude yeah,
I can lend money to that person.

00:29:20.010 --> 00:29:21.910
They're going to be good
for it because double A,

00:29:21.910 --> 00:29:24.110 position:56%
it's like triple A with bonds today.

00:29:24.110 --> 00:29:28.380 position:56%
It's the highest, most credit-worthy
category you can imagine.

00:29:28.380 --> 00:29:30.100
And these things got published.

00:29:30.100 --> 00:29:32.120
They were, you know,
constantly being updated.

00:29:32.120 --> 00:29:34.300
Originally they were published
annually and then twice

00:29:34.300 --> 00:29:35.750
and then four times a year.

00:29:35.750 --> 00:29:38.150
And the wonderful thing
about this method is

00:29:38.150 --> 00:29:40.450
that it was very scaleable.

00:29:40.450 --> 00:29:44.220
That is, you could take this and
apply it to a small community

00:29:44.220 --> 00:29:46.250
or to a small part of the country.

00:29:46.250 --> 00:29:50.890 position:56%
But you could also blow it up and
just keep on adding new communities,

00:29:50.890 --> 00:29:52.510
gathering more information,

00:29:52.510 --> 00:29:57.050
and gradually building an ever-more
encompassing network of information

00:29:57.050 --> 00:30:00.170
that basically captured everyone.

00:30:00.170 --> 00:30:03.240 position:56%
So here are two -- this little chart
gives you two pieces of information

00:30:03.240 --> 00:30:05.710
about the growth of
the Mercantile Agency.

00:30:05.710 --> 00:30:14.140
One on the -- let's see -- it's the
little red purple, I think it looks

00:30:14.140 --> 00:30:16.870
like on the left-hand
scale, gives you the number

00:30:16.870 --> 00:30:18.620
of firms that were being rated.

00:30:18.620 --> 00:30:22.370
And when they started to do rating
books at the end of the 1850s,

00:30:22.370 --> 00:30:24.650
they rated about 20,000 firms.

00:30:24.650 --> 00:30:28.930
So that's, you know, in this
ink and paper kind of method.

00:30:28.930 --> 00:30:32.050
But by the end of the 19th century,
they're well into the millions.

00:30:32.050 --> 00:30:34.970
Okay? So it's a giant scale.

00:30:34.970 --> 00:30:37.790
They're providing more
information about businesses

00:30:37.790 --> 00:30:40.940
than anyone else in
the United States.

00:30:40.940 --> 00:30:44.520
And then their firm itself
grew, and I used the number

00:30:44.520 --> 00:30:46.880
of branch offices to track that.

00:30:46.880 --> 00:30:51.850 position:56%
They start, of course, with one
office when they're founded in 1841.

00:30:51.850 --> 00:30:53.940
And that's the right-hand scale.

00:30:53.940 --> 00:30:56.600
And there are a couple of
periods where they plateau.

00:30:56.600 --> 00:30:58.390
That is, they don't expand much.

00:30:58.390 --> 00:31:00.010
The Civil War is one.

00:31:00.010 --> 00:31:02.300
The recession of the
1890s is another.

00:31:02.300 --> 00:31:04.500
But basically they
grow phenomenally.

00:31:04.500 --> 00:31:07.510
So this is a wildly
successful business.

00:31:07.510 --> 00:31:09.890
Providing information
about the trustworthiness

00:31:09.890 --> 00:31:13.830
of others is a great way to
make a buck in the 19th century.

00:31:13.830 --> 00:31:17.810
Because there was such demand for
information that creditors can use

00:31:17.810 --> 00:31:20.200
to resolve this problem
of uncertainty.

00:31:20.200 --> 00:31:22.880
And it's not a national story.

00:31:22.880 --> 00:31:24.490
They go overseas.

00:31:24.490 --> 00:31:28.080
And so this, in 1916, is
from one of their documents

00:31:28.080 --> 00:31:31.030
that gives the branch
offices that are abroad.

00:31:31.030 --> 00:31:32.470
They go into Canada.

00:31:32.470 --> 00:31:33.780
They go to Europe.

00:31:33.780 --> 00:31:35.630
They go to Australia.

00:31:35.630 --> 00:31:37.530
Latin, you know, South America.

00:31:37.530 --> 00:31:39.090
They're all over the place.

00:31:39.090 --> 00:31:45.180
And just to give you a sense --
you know, in 1916, let's see.

00:31:45.180 --> 00:31:48.370
Perth, Australia, you
know, in Western Australia.

00:31:48.370 --> 00:31:51.820
In 1916, there wasn't a
lot going on in Perth.

00:31:51.820 --> 00:31:55.460
Right? But whatever was going on
in Perth, you would know about it,

00:31:55.460 --> 00:31:59.320
if you were a subscriber
to Dun's Mercantile Agency.

00:31:59.320 --> 00:32:03.280
That's how panoptic and
encompassing the scope was.

00:32:03.280 --> 00:32:06.410
So the information, as
I said, is gathered,

00:32:06.410 --> 00:32:09.320
and it's kept in these
proprietary ledgers,

00:32:09.320 --> 00:32:11.420
but then it gets turned
into a score.

00:32:11.420 --> 00:32:13.190
And the key evolves over time,

00:32:13.190 --> 00:32:16.990
but one thing that doesn't
change is the fact that the key,

00:32:16.990 --> 00:32:20.200
or the information that
gets sold to the customer,

00:32:20.200 --> 00:32:24.890
is always cast as a
ordered category.

00:32:24.890 --> 00:32:27.400
It's always a matter
of classifying a firm.

00:32:27.400 --> 00:32:30.970
And so the first category system,
the first ordinal category system

00:32:30.970 --> 00:32:35.670
from 1859, has at the top A number
one, then number one, then one

00:32:35.670 --> 00:32:37.230
and a half, two, and so forth.

00:32:37.230 --> 00:32:38.980
So you can see the order.

00:32:38.980 --> 00:32:42.220
And the meaning of A
number one is the following.

00:32:42.220 --> 00:32:44.690
Of longstanding, good antecedents.

00:32:44.690 --> 00:32:46.870
Business comparatively
devoid of hazard.

00:32:46.870 --> 00:32:50.200
Ample means in and large
wealth out of business.

00:32:50.200 --> 00:32:51.500
Credit unlimited.

00:32:51.500 --> 00:32:54.540
So that's as good as you
were going to get in 1859.

00:32:54.540 --> 00:32:57.690
That was just a way of saying
throw money at this borrower

00:32:57.690 --> 00:32:59.140
because they're going to be fine.

00:32:59.140 --> 00:33:02.490
And then, of course, you
work your way down the scale.

00:33:02.490 --> 00:33:07.610
And, in the early 1850,
excuse me, late 1850s --

00:33:07.610 --> 00:33:10.350
and here's something from
the Banker's magazine.

00:33:10.350 --> 00:33:15.300 position:56%
It's clear that the larger business
community recognized the value here.

00:33:15.300 --> 00:33:17.670
So it wasn't just that they
were promoting themselves

00:33:17.670 --> 00:33:19.570
and saying this is
great information.

00:33:19.570 --> 00:33:22.600
There were authorities like
bankers who also weighed in.

00:33:22.600 --> 00:33:25.850
And said, for example, the
valuable services it --

00:33:25.850 --> 00:33:28.670
the Mercantile Agency -- has
rendered to the domestic trade

00:33:28.670 --> 00:33:32.720
of the country as a check upon
our credit system are acknowledged

00:33:32.720 --> 00:33:34.390
by the mercantile community.

00:33:34.390 --> 00:33:36.790
So this is basically a way
of recognizing the fact

00:33:36.790 --> 00:33:40.020
that this stuff seemed
to really work for those

00:33:40.020 --> 00:33:42.510
who used it, this information.

00:33:42.510 --> 00:33:44.620
So one of the interesting
things that happens

00:33:44.620 --> 00:33:47.180
over time is the evolution
of the category system.

00:33:47.180 --> 00:33:50.750
So the first one from 1859.

00:33:50.750 --> 00:33:53.840
Now we have a two-dimensional
category system,

00:33:53.840 --> 00:33:57.480
where we've got A plus on top
and then A, B, C, you know,

00:33:57.480 --> 00:34:00.650
all the way down to L. And
then on the right-hand column,

00:34:00.650 --> 00:34:02.560
you've got A1, and this use

00:34:02.560 --> 00:34:05.010
of alphanumeric labels
underscores the fact

00:34:05.010 --> 00:34:07.010
that these are ordered categories.

00:34:07.010 --> 00:34:09.430
Here we've got more
ordered categories

00:34:09.430 --> 00:34:11.570
from the Mercantile
Agency in British Columbia

00:34:11.570 --> 00:34:14.850
at the end of the 19th century.

00:34:14.850 --> 00:34:19.660
And another congratulatory
headline from the Chicago Tribune.

00:34:19.660 --> 00:34:20.960
The headline says it all.

00:34:20.960 --> 00:34:24.890
The Mercantile Agencies, They Have
Grown Indispensable to Business.

00:34:24.890 --> 00:34:27.970
So this is a thing that really
took off and really locked

00:34:27.970 --> 00:34:31.160
in to the American
business community.

00:34:31.160 --> 00:34:33.360
And one of the interesting
things about it is that,

00:34:33.360 --> 00:34:35.690
although in its origins
it really dealt

00:34:35.690 --> 00:34:39.950
with short-term unsecured
trade credit,

00:34:39.950 --> 00:34:45.630
it gained such a powerful hold over
the ways in which people started

00:34:45.630 --> 00:34:47.950
to think about credit
and credit worthiness.

00:34:47.950 --> 00:34:51.750
That it was very natural for
John Moody, when he started

00:34:51.750 --> 00:34:55.110
to rate railway bonds in 1909,

00:34:55.110 --> 00:34:58.730
that he would adopt essentially
the same kind of system.

00:34:58.730 --> 00:35:01.350
So when we get into long-term
bonds, which, as you know,

00:35:01.350 --> 00:35:04.130
is a very different kind of
credit problem, you know,

00:35:04.130 --> 00:35:07.020
for capital intensive businesses.

00:35:07.020 --> 00:35:11.450 position:56%
Like the railroads or for sovereigns
or for any of this other big stuff.

00:35:11.450 --> 00:35:14.070
It was natural to use
the ordered categories.

00:35:14.070 --> 00:35:15.830
So here we've got John
Moody who started

00:35:15.830 --> 00:35:18.400
to rate railway bonds in 1909.

00:35:18.400 --> 00:35:22.300 position:56%
And I don't happen to have the slide
of the 1909 ordinal categories.

00:35:22.300 --> 00:35:24.650
But, in 1912, it's the same setup.

00:35:24.650 --> 00:35:28.100
And you can see at the top
is triple A and then double A

00:35:28.100 --> 00:35:32.070
and then A. Very much
like a modern bond rating.

00:35:32.070 --> 00:35:35.550
So Moody basically
said this great system

00:35:35.550 --> 00:35:40.700 position:56%
for assessing short-term unsecured
trade credit and the trustworthiness

00:35:40.700 --> 00:35:44.500
of borrowers in that world,
I'm simply going to apply

00:35:44.500 --> 00:35:48.250
to long-term corporate debt,
starting with the railroads.

00:35:48.250 --> 00:35:49.550
And it worked.

00:35:49.550 --> 00:35:53.660
He succeeded just as well
as the predecessors had.

00:35:53.660 --> 00:35:55.540
And we can move forward in time.

00:35:55.540 --> 00:35:58.320
And here's Standard &amp; Poor's
and other bond-rating agency

00:35:58.320 --> 00:36:00.550
from the late 1940s, and again,

00:36:00.550 --> 00:36:03.420
you see the same old
ordinal category system.

00:36:03.420 --> 00:36:06.500
So this way of thinking
about trustworthiness

00:36:06.500 --> 00:36:08.990
as somehow involving categorization

00:36:08.990 --> 00:36:12.610
into an ordered category
system really gets locked in

00:36:12.610 --> 00:36:14.210
and is reproduced going forward.

00:36:14.210 --> 00:36:15.640
Even as, of course, the world

00:36:15.640 --> 00:36:19.190
of business is changing,
this system does not.

00:36:19.190 --> 00:36:23.620
And so we have Dun &amp;
Bradstreet categories from 1960

00:36:23.620 --> 00:36:27.630
and ratings are breaking
out all over,

00:36:27.630 --> 00:36:31.660
so you could find a rating book
for a particular firm or excuse me,

00:36:31.660 --> 00:36:33.080
for a particular location.

00:36:33.080 --> 00:36:35.390
In this case, Cleveland.

00:36:35.390 --> 00:36:36.980
And this is -- I just note --

00:36:36.980 --> 00:36:39.550
is around the same time that
the Cubs last won the World

00:36:39.550 --> 00:36:40.850
Series [laughter].

00:36:40.850 --> 00:36:42.150
Isn't that interesting?

00:36:42.150 --> 00:36:43.450
How did that get in there?

00:36:43.450 --> 00:36:48.590
Anyway, so this kind of thing
is going on all the time.

00:36:48.590 --> 00:36:52.970
If you wanted to sell goods to an
individual in Cleveland in 1909,

00:36:52.970 --> 00:36:55.230
you would be a subscriber
to a volume such as this.

00:36:55.230 --> 00:36:57.290
And you would look
up the person's name.

00:36:57.290 --> 00:37:00.230
And this is for individuals
now, not for businesses.

00:37:00.230 --> 00:37:03.160
And you'd look them up and they
might be given an A rating,

00:37:03.160 --> 00:37:05.100
in which case they'd
be a good customer,

00:37:05.100 --> 00:37:08.390
or they might be given an F
rating, which means not so good.

00:37:08.390 --> 00:37:09.690
And so forth.

00:37:09.690 --> 00:37:12.420
There were ratings that
were attached to industries.

00:37:12.420 --> 00:37:15.340
And so here's the seafood
industry in 1913.

00:37:15.340 --> 00:37:16.640
Same story.

00:37:16.640 --> 00:37:20.220
This, as an idiom for
examining or for gathering

00:37:20.220 --> 00:37:21.520
and portraying information

00:37:21.520 --> 00:37:24.130
about trustworthiness
becomes very widespread.

00:37:24.130 --> 00:37:27.860
So one of the big issues,
one of the big mysteries

00:37:27.860 --> 00:37:31.080
to this project is how
useful were these ratings?

00:37:31.080 --> 00:37:36.270
They obviously succeeded, in the
sense that the business of creating

00:37:36.270 --> 00:37:39.330
and selling ratings spread.

00:37:39.330 --> 00:37:43.250
But did they actually -- what did
they actually do for the users?

00:37:43.250 --> 00:37:46.870
And here, the credit raters
themselves made very strong --

00:37:46.870 --> 00:37:50.010
but I would say ambiguous
claims -- about their ratings.

00:37:50.010 --> 00:37:52.100
Which is to say they would insist

00:37:52.100 --> 00:37:55.660
that their customers will do very
well to pay for the information

00:37:55.660 --> 00:37:57.190
that they were going to sell.

00:37:57.190 --> 00:38:00.680
But they were a little canny about
saying, by the way, you'll be able

00:38:00.680 --> 00:38:02.820
to predict who's going
to fail and who not,

00:38:02.820 --> 00:38:04.810 position:56%
if you subscribe to our information.

00:38:04.810 --> 00:38:09.240
They kind of fudged and hedged
when it came to that kind of stuff.

00:38:09.240 --> 00:38:12.410
So one -- in another
stage of my project,

00:38:12.410 --> 00:38:14.160
what I did was gather a data set

00:38:14.160 --> 00:38:20.230
of 247 Chicago dry
goods firms from 1879.

00:38:20.230 --> 00:38:21.530
And what I've done is --

00:38:21.530 --> 00:38:24.610 position:56%
and I picked dry goods firms because
these were sort of the predecessors

00:38:24.610 --> 00:38:26.470
of the modern department store,

00:38:26.470 --> 00:38:29.490
and they were very heavily
embedded in credit networks.

00:38:29.490 --> 00:38:32.420
That is, they obtained
credit from their suppliers.

00:38:32.420 --> 00:38:35.190
They extended credit
to their customers.

00:38:35.190 --> 00:38:39.200
And so they -- for them, in
particular, good management

00:38:39.200 --> 00:38:43.260
of credit was absolutely
critical to their success.

00:38:43.260 --> 00:38:46.030
And, of course, Chicago in
the 1870s is a booming place,

00:38:46.030 --> 00:38:47.370
with lots of business.

00:38:47.370 --> 00:38:51.200
And so the population of dry
goods firms is expanding.

00:38:51.200 --> 00:38:53.060
There're new funds being added.

00:38:53.060 --> 00:38:55.820
There's old ones going
bankrupt and so forth.

00:38:55.820 --> 00:39:00.870 position:56%
And what I did in this project was
to link that proprietary information

00:39:00.870 --> 00:39:02.260
that you've seen that was contained

00:39:02.260 --> 00:39:05.600
in the ledgers to the
published rating.

00:39:05.600 --> 00:39:09.100
And then to see does
that predict failure

00:39:09.100 --> 00:39:12.040
or distress of the rated firm?

00:39:12.040 --> 00:39:14.750
That is, could you use the rating

00:39:14.750 --> 00:39:17.270
to predict who's going
to fail and who not?

00:39:17.270 --> 00:39:20.510
Who would be a good risk?

00:39:20.510 --> 00:39:21.810
And who not?

00:39:21.810 --> 00:39:25.760
And there are multiple rating
agencies working at this time.

00:39:25.760 --> 00:39:27.060
There's Dun.

00:39:27.060 --> 00:39:28.360
There's Bradstreet.

