00:52:50.960 --> 00:52:54.540
of the baggage of science
and accuracy and so on.

00:52:54.540 --> 00:52:57.990
But, in fact, I want to
remind you that there is a --

00:52:57.990 --> 00:53:02.250
it's much less a happy
story of progress.

00:53:02.250 --> 00:53:05.600
So when all of that massive
information gets boiled

00:53:05.600 --> 00:53:08.580
down into a single rating or score,

00:53:08.580 --> 00:53:13.000
simplification necessarily
excludes lots of information.

00:53:13.000 --> 00:53:15.190
That is, you may think [inaudible]
there's the cloud of noise

00:53:15.190 --> 00:53:17.520
and now we're going
to have the signal.

00:53:17.520 --> 00:53:19.610
But, in fact, the signal
ignores a lot

00:53:19.610 --> 00:53:22.540
of the information that's
contained in that cloud.

00:53:22.540 --> 00:53:24.600
I got to stop waving my hands here.

00:53:24.600 --> 00:53:27.910
And so, for example, the
relationality [phonetic] of credit.

00:53:27.910 --> 00:53:29.720
The fact that trust is relational.

00:53:29.720 --> 00:53:31.630
It's between two individuals.

00:53:31.630 --> 00:53:34.400
That gets lost because the score
gets attached to the debtor

00:53:34.400 --> 00:53:38.880
and the fact that how credit worthy
you are always really matters

00:53:38.880 --> 00:53:40.490
in relation to whom.

00:53:40.490 --> 00:53:43.500
You know, I, as a borrower,
am probably more credit worthy

00:53:43.500 --> 00:53:46.380
in relation to my sister
than I am to my bank.

00:53:46.380 --> 00:53:48.950
You know, if my bank
lends me 100 bucks.

00:53:48.950 --> 00:53:52.050
Well, you know, I'll try to
repay them, but if my sister,

00:53:52.050 --> 00:53:53.350
you know, lends me 100 bucks.

00:53:53.350 --> 00:53:54.860
Well, I'm really going to
take care of my sister.

00:53:54.860 --> 00:53:58.230
Right? Because our relation is
very strong unlike the relation

00:53:58.230 --> 00:54:00.850
between myself and my bank.

00:54:00.850 --> 00:54:03.140
And that fact is ignored.

00:54:03.140 --> 00:54:05.490
That's lost in this scoring.

00:54:05.490 --> 00:54:08.840
There's a lot of ambiguous
and conflicting information

00:54:08.840 --> 00:54:12.770
and what you get is a very precise
well-calibrated, unambiguous score.

00:54:12.770 --> 00:54:15.660
You are exactly double A or
triple A or whatever it is.

00:54:15.660 --> 00:54:19.920
But, in fact, the real fact
of your life or the real fact

00:54:19.920 --> 00:54:23.220
of the borrower is
much more ambiguous

00:54:23.220 --> 00:54:26.090
and so why do we make
ambiguity go away?

00:54:26.090 --> 00:54:28.070
Right? That's definitely a loss.

00:54:28.070 --> 00:54:30.260
The information is of
variable provenance.

00:54:30.260 --> 00:54:33.910
Some of it comes from very credible
sources and some of it from not.

00:54:33.910 --> 00:54:36.250
You know, some of it is
really gossip and hearsay.

00:54:36.250 --> 00:54:40.460
All of that variable provenance
gets lost in the score.

00:54:40.460 --> 00:54:43.600
The measurement process
itself is highly reactive.

00:54:43.600 --> 00:54:48.680
That is, when Dun sent a
staff member to a business

00:54:48.680 --> 00:54:50.570
and said tell us about
your business.

00:54:50.570 --> 00:54:54.660
That business would go,
oh, it's the guys from Dun.

00:54:54.660 --> 00:54:55.960
I better tell a good story.

00:54:55.960 --> 00:54:58.660
I better make myself look good
because what they conclude

00:54:58.660 --> 00:55:01.610
about me is going to affect
my life going forward.

00:55:01.610 --> 00:55:05.210
If they like me, I get a high
score, and I get lots of credit.

00:55:05.210 --> 00:55:06.520
And if they don't.

00:55:06.520 --> 00:55:09.860
Right? So they would try
to game the information.

00:55:09.860 --> 00:55:13.090
And, of course, Dun was mindful
of that, so they would try

00:55:13.090 --> 00:55:15.700
to make adjustments for
whether they were being gamed.

00:55:15.700 --> 00:55:17.520
And so the whole thing
was very reactive.

00:55:17.520 --> 00:55:21.460
And of course the rating
process itself was very opaque.

00:55:21.460 --> 00:55:24.440
We see a very substantial
increase in the scale and scope

00:55:24.440 --> 00:55:25.760
of this information system.

00:55:25.760 --> 00:55:29.090
And one of the reasons
that we use it today is

00:55:29.090 --> 00:55:34.040
because it has this strong affinity
with algorithmic decision-making.

00:55:34.040 --> 00:55:36.340
And you can see that in
the early 20th century,

00:55:36.340 --> 00:55:39.570
in the way in which
credit insurance is priced.

00:55:39.570 --> 00:55:42.810
But the fact that you can go online

00:55:42.810 --> 00:55:45.050
and enter your social
security number.

00:55:45.050 --> 00:55:47.590
And someone can link
that to your FICO score,

00:55:47.590 --> 00:55:49.650
and in 30 seconds give you a loan.

00:55:49.650 --> 00:55:58.980
That only works because there
is a background of algorithms

00:55:58.980 --> 00:56:02.630
and databases that can
construct a simple rule.

00:56:02.630 --> 00:56:06.900
You know? That the algorithm
will spit out a yes or a no,

00:56:06.900 --> 00:56:08.630
depending upon your score.

00:56:08.630 --> 00:56:11.350
And they'll do it very
quickly at computer speed.

00:56:11.350 --> 00:56:14.080
And it's not that there's a loan
officer at the other end of that.

00:56:14.080 --> 00:56:17.030
It's completely outside
of human hands.

00:56:17.030 --> 00:56:21.650 position:56%
Right? So when you have quantitative
information about trustworthiness,

00:56:21.650 --> 00:56:25.830 position:56%
you can build a computer program to
make the lending decisions that used

00:56:25.830 --> 00:56:27.520
to be made by individuals.

00:56:27.520 --> 00:56:28.820
And that, of course, allows you

00:56:28.820 --> 00:56:30.970
to make decisions on
a much bigger scale.

00:56:30.970 --> 00:56:34.090
To do so much more
cheaply but not necessarily

00:56:34.090 --> 00:56:35.670
to make better decisions.

00:56:35.670 --> 00:56:38.480 position:56%
These numbers are portable, and
they are used in different contexts.

00:56:38.480 --> 00:56:39.780
And so now what we've started

00:56:39.780 --> 00:56:43.850
to realize is how much FICO scores
not only govern access to credit

00:56:43.850 --> 00:56:46.090
but also govern access
to employment.

00:56:46.090 --> 00:56:48.970
Employers pay attention
to FICO scores.

00:56:48.970 --> 00:56:51.370
Insurance companies pay
attention to FICO scores.

00:56:51.370 --> 00:56:55.200
Your auto insurance may be
priced depending upon your score.

00:56:55.200 --> 00:56:57.560
Landlords pay attention
to your FICO score.

00:56:57.560 --> 00:57:00.370
It's hard to rent an apartment
if you have a low score

00:57:00.370 --> 00:57:01.720
because the landlord
will say no, no, no.

00:57:01.720 --> 00:57:03.150
I don't want you as a tenant.

00:57:03.150 --> 00:57:05.760
Right? So your fate in
many, many different parts

00:57:05.760 --> 00:57:07.680
of life are suddenly --
is going to get driven

00:57:07.680 --> 00:57:09.990
by this one piece of information.

00:57:09.990 --> 00:57:14.030
And, as I said, these
measures have been commodified.

00:57:14.030 --> 00:57:15.430
And their legal status.

00:57:15.430 --> 00:57:18.300
You know what sort of liabilities

00:57:18.300 --> 00:57:22.430
and obligations are attended upon
them often drive what's going

00:57:22.430 --> 00:57:25.550
on with that information much
more than their veracity.

00:57:25.550 --> 00:57:29.280
It's not simply a story of good
science and getting it right.

00:57:29.280 --> 00:57:31.990
It's much more what
are my obligations?

00:57:31.990 --> 00:57:34.900
And what are my vulnerabilities?

00:57:34.900 --> 00:57:38.130
And, of course, credit itself
remains a very interesting

00:57:38.130 --> 00:57:39.430
and contentious issue.

00:57:39.430 --> 00:57:41.160
And so I'm almost done here.

