you a reference book.

01:02:40.790 --> 01:02:43.570
And you would use that, you know,
to decide which bonds you wanted

01:02:43.570 --> 01:02:45.520
to buy, if you were
managing a pension fund

01:02:45.520 --> 01:02:46.820
or some sort of portfolio.

01:02:46.820 --> 01:02:52.020
But starting in the 1970s, you
know, for a number of reasons,

01:02:52.020 --> 01:02:55.180
one of which was the growing
use of the photocopier,

01:02:55.180 --> 01:02:58.590
piracy really became a problem
for the bond rating agencies.

01:02:58.590 --> 01:03:00.210
Which is to say they -- anyone

01:03:00.210 --> 01:03:03.190
with a photocopy machine could take
their reference books and start

01:03:03.190 --> 01:03:05.540
to make multiple copies and
share them with their friends.

01:03:05.540 --> 01:03:08.380
And so they were losing
money on that front.

01:03:08.380 --> 01:03:15.280 position:56%
But also the failure of Penn Central
was a real shock to bond markets,

01:03:15.280 --> 01:03:20.270 position:56%
and Penn Central was a big railroad,
very blue chip, very unexpected.

01:03:20.270 --> 01:03:23.250
And because they'd been given a
high rating and because they failed

01:03:23.250 --> 01:03:27.120 position:56%
so spectacularly, a lot of investors
basically started to wonder well,

01:03:27.120 --> 01:03:29.510
can we really trust
any of these ratings?

01:03:29.510 --> 01:03:32.520
And so what happened
was a lot of issuers.

01:03:32.520 --> 01:03:37.370
That is, a lot of companies that
had issued bonds basically paid the

01:03:37.370 --> 01:03:40.450
rating agencies to
rerate their bonds.

01:03:40.450 --> 01:03:42.970
And the rating agencies
realized oh my gosh,

01:03:42.970 --> 01:03:45.610
we could have an issuer-pays
business model.

01:03:45.610 --> 01:03:49.380
And then the piracy stuff doesn't
matter as much because the person,

01:03:49.380 --> 01:03:52.600
you know, the cash now
comes from the firm

01:03:52.600 --> 01:03:54.360
that wants to sell the bonds.

01:03:54.360 --> 01:03:57.920
But that, as we saw in
the lead up to 2008,

01:03:57.920 --> 01:04:00.430 position:56%
creates a real conflict of interest.

01:04:00.430 --> 01:04:03.630
Which is to say the rating
agency, their customers,

01:04:03.630 --> 01:04:07.210
not the person that's using the
information and who therefore would

01:04:07.210 --> 01:04:09.290
like to have information
that was accurate.

01:04:09.290 --> 01:04:14.390
It's the entity that is trying to
borrow money and therefore would

01:04:14.390 --> 01:04:17.140
like as high a rating as possible.

01:04:17.140 --> 01:04:20.260
Because if you have a high
rating, it's lower interest rates.

01:04:20.260 --> 01:04:22.030
You borrow more money more cheaply.

01:04:22.030 --> 01:04:23.340
There's a better market.

01:04:23.340 --> 01:04:24.910
All that kind of stuff.

01:04:24.910 --> 01:04:29.450
And so that conflict of interest
really reared its ugly head leading

01:04:29.450 --> 01:04:30.750
up to 2008.

01:04:30.750 --> 01:04:33.730
And I guess the other thing
that happened in the runup

01:04:33.730 --> 01:04:38.860
and that really, you know,
worried people was the fact

01:04:38.860 --> 01:04:42.780
that this is an apparatus, and
