well it's triple A. It's kind of
like a triple A, you know GE bond.

01:05:56.230 --> 01:05:59.010
So all you need to know
is it's triple A. Right?

01:05:59.010 --> 01:06:00.700
It's going to be a good investment.

01:06:00.700 --> 01:06:04.710
So a lot of the financial
shenanigans and the complexity kind

01:06:04.710 --> 01:06:08.200
of got masked by the use of
this very familiar label.

01:06:08.200 --> 01:06:11.940
And that, of course,
masked an enormous amount

01:06:11.940 --> 01:06:17.830
of heterogeneity and,
you know, bad, bad risks.

01:06:17.830 --> 01:06:22.750
So you know, as 2008 went forward,

01:06:22.750 --> 01:06:28.510
especially the subprime-backed
mortgage-backed securities

01:06:28.510 --> 01:06:29.810
just plummeted.

01:06:29.810 --> 01:06:32.080
They, a bunch of them had
been given triple A ratings,

01:06:32.080 --> 01:06:35.550
which were obviously was
wildly inappropriate.

01:06:35.550 --> 01:06:39.770
And, as the real estate markets
in Florida and Southern California

01:06:39.770 --> 01:06:45.010 position:56%
and Arizona caved, those things
started to experience defaults rates

01:06:45.010 --> 01:06:48.170 position:56%
that were far, many orders of
magnitude higher than you should get

01:06:48.170 --> 01:06:51.950
with triple A. So I think
-- and you know with --

01:06:51.950 --> 01:06:56.610
and then people realized, as
you finally put your finger on,

01:06:56.610 --> 01:07:01.000
that this NRSRO [phonetic] status
was a kind of a special status.

01:07:01.000 --> 01:07:03.440
It was bestowed on a
small number of firms.

01:07:03.440 --> 01:07:05.860
And so leading up to [inaudible],

01:07:05.860 --> 01:07:07.330
there was a very interesting
conversation

01:07:07.330 --> 01:07:08.790
of whether this was a market

01:07:08.790 --> 01:07:11.530
in which we should have
more competition or less.

01:07:11.530 --> 01:07:15.140 position:56%
Right? More competition means we
allow other firms to kind of join in

01:07:15.140 --> 01:07:17.310
and compete with them
maybe to do a better a job.

01:07:17.310 --> 01:07:20.840
But here that intuition
runs up against the fact

01:07:20.840 --> 01:07:24.400
that with issuer-pays business
model, they're competing

01:07:24.400 --> 01:07:26.350
for the business of the issuers.

01:07:26.350 --> 01:07:30.360
And so, in fact, the competition
could drive them to be even laxer

01:07:30.360 --> 01:07:33.370
and more non-rigorous
than the other way around.

01:07:33.370 --> 01:07:36.750
Because they all want
the issuer to use them,

01:07:36.750 --> 01:07:38.570
to hire them to rate the bonds.

01:07:38.570 --> 01:07:41.710
And the way in which you get
the issuer to use your service

01:07:41.710 --> 01:07:44.080
as opposed to Moody's,
if you're S&amp;P,

01:07:44.080 --> 01:07:46.780
is to come up with a nicer
rating, a higher rating

01:07:46.780 --> 01:07:48.740
for the same set of securities.

01:07:48.740 --> 01:07:51.390
Which is going to push you in
the direction of making mistakes

01:07:51.390 --> 01:07:53.720
and being overly optimistic
and all that kind of stuff.

01:07:53.720 --> 01:07:57.690
So I think it turned out
that the matter of, you know,

01:07:57.690 --> 01:08:00.330
do we want more competition
in this market or less?

01:08:00.330 --> 01:08:03.230
It actually turned out to
be a little more complicated

01:08:03.230 --> 01:08:05.880
than people thought.

01:08:05.880 --> 01:08:08.180
&gt;&gt; You have time for
one more question.

01:08:13.000 --> 01:08:16.130 position:56%
&gt;&gt; [Inaudible] mentioned towards the
end that this was a US origin story.

01:08:16.130 --> 01:08:17.890
And I was wondering --
there was a -- I mean --

01:08:17.890 --> 01:08:19.200
there's been colonial trade

01:08:19.200 --> 01:08:21.090
and colonial trade
must have had some kind

01:08:21.090 --> 01:08:22.910
of credit rating system
of some sort.

01:08:22.910 --> 01:08:24.270
And so I'm wondering
what they did instead.

01:08:24.270 --> 01:08:27.630
&gt;&gt; Bruce Carruthers: So I
didn't really emphasize this,

01:08:27.630 --> 01:08:30.590
but before ratings
came along, of course,

01:08:30.590 --> 01:08:34.200
credit pervades Colonial
and early America.

01:08:34.200 --> 01:08:35.940
But there are no ratings.

01:08:35.940 --> 01:08:37.850
But what you have is reliance

01:08:37.850 --> 01:08:41.200
on very old-fashioned
social network-based.

01:08:41.200 --> 01:08:42.890
You know, are we part
of the same community?

01:08:42.890 --> 01:08:44.340
What's your reputation?

01:08:44.340 --> 01:08:46.690
If I don't know who you are
directly, I know someone

01:08:46.690 --> 01:08:48.710
who knows you, so direct ties.

01:08:48.710 --> 01:08:50.010
Indirect ties.

01:08:50.010 --> 01:08:53.580
You know, kind of very
much a kind of the reliance

01:08:53.580 --> 01:08:55.770
on existing social
networks, friendship,

01:08:55.770 --> 01:08:57.070
kinship, acquaintanceship.

01:08:57.070 --> 01:08:58.420
You know, however they're styled.

01:08:58.420 --> 01:09:01.870 position:56%
To circulate the kind of
information about who's trustworthy.

01:09:01.870 --> 01:09:05.690
And it turns out that does
characterize the United States

01:09:05.690 --> 01:09:07.780
before, and it also
actually characterizes a lot

01:09:07.780 --> 01:09:09.080
of colonial trade.

01:09:09.080 --> 01:09:12.100
There were a few more network
businesses than the colonial trade,

01:09:12.100 --> 01:09:15.610
so it was a small number,
you know, of major firms

01:09:15.610 --> 01:09:19.760
who mediated trade between, you
know, England and Colonial America.

01:09:19.760 --> 01:09:23.850
And within that, you know,
geographically dispersed

01:09:23.850 --> 01:09:26.780
but socially compact group,

01:09:26.780 --> 01:09:30.960
you could actually do quite a
good job circulating reputations.

01:09:30.960 --> 01:09:33.340
And so they really
didn't need ratings.

01:09:33.340 --> 01:09:36.270
It's when you start to deal
with a high volume of people

01:09:36.270 --> 01:09:40.390
who are really true strangers
to you that you need to look

01:09:40.390 --> 01:09:41.690
for a different solution.

01:09:41.690 --> 01:09:46.870 position:56%
And that, it turns out, broke out
mostly with a growing domestic trade

01:09:46.870 --> 01:09:51.830
in the US where, you know, if you
were a New York City supplier.

01:09:51.830 --> 01:09:55.740
The New York area, you could find
out what's going on pretty easily.

01:09:55.740 --> 01:09:59.090
But somebody from the Midwest,
in a city like Chicago,

01:09:59.090 --> 01:10:00.730
you have no idea what's
going on there.

01:10:00.730 --> 01:10:02.520
You don't know any of those people.

01:10:02.520 --> 01:10:03.820
They're all strangers to you.

01:10:03.820 --> 01:10:06.190
And you don't have any direct
or indirect network ties

01:10:06.190 --> 01:10:08.280
into that community, so
you're really looking

01:10:08.280 --> 01:10:09.580
for someone to help you out.

01:10:09.580 --> 01:10:11.480
And that's why they stepped up.

01:10:11.480 --> 01:10:14.140
So, if you look at the
establishment of the railroads

01:10:14.140 --> 01:10:15.670
and denser distribution

01:10:15.670 --> 01:10:18.000
and transportation
linkages domestically.

01:10:18.000 --> 01:10:21.370 position:56%
That really opened up an
opportunity for the rating agencies.

01:10:21.370 --> 01:10:23.410
But, you know, the
question's a good one.

01:10:23.410 --> 01:10:26.410
I think the old-fashioned
solution of, you know,

01:10:26.410 --> 01:10:28.850
rely on social networks, you know.

01:10:28.850 --> 01:10:30.210
And because I know
you're a sociologist

01:10:30.210 --> 01:10:33.530
that probably doesn't
make you too mad.

01:10:33.530 --> 01:10:35.470
That actually works
with colonial trade

01:10:35.470 --> 01:10:38.690
and a surprising amount
of long distance trade.

